cs.DC, cs.DS, cs.CC, cs.GT, cs.IT. 

This paper deals with complexity in the LOCAL model, which is a distributed computing model. Therefore, cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses algorithms for graph problems such as maximal matching, MIS, vertex coloring, and edge-coloring, which fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also establishes connections between deterministic and randomized complexities, which could fall under cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the paper uses the graph shattering technique, which is a tool used in cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
